{
  "idea": {
    "Name": "kernel_aware_kv_cache_reordering",
    "Title": "Kernel-Aware KV Cache Reordering for Efficient Long-Context LLM Inference",
    "Short Hypothesis": "Reordering the KV cache layout to align with kernel-level memory access patterns can significantly improve tensor-core utilization and reduce memory-bandwidth bottlenecks during long-context LLM inference.",
    "Related Work": "BitDecoding optimizes low-bit KV cache quantization for Tensor Core utilization but does not address cache layout reordering. This proposal focuses on cache-aware reordering, leveraging kernel-level memory access patterns to improve efficiency.",
    "Abstract": "Long-context Large Language Models (LLMs) face significant memory-bandwidth bottlenecks due to inefficient Key-Value (KV) cache layouts. Existing approaches, such as low-bit quantization, improve memory footprint but neglect kernel-level memory access patterns. We propose Kernel-Aware KV Cache Reordering, a novel method that dynamically reorders the KV cache to align with CUDA/Triton kernel memory access patterns. This optimization maximizes tensor-core utilization and reduces memory-bandwidth bottlenecks. Our experiments on LLaMA-3.1-8B with 128K context demonstrate a 3.5× reduction in decoding latency, attributed to improved warp coalescing and reduced HBM round-trips. We validate our approach using nvprof/Nsight traces, reporting warp stall reasons, arithmetic intensity, and achieved bandwidth. The results show that Kernel-Aware KV Cache Reordering significantly outperforms state-of-the-art methods like BitDecoding in end-to-end inference speed.",
