{
  "idea": {
    "Name": "task_dependent_compressibility",
    "Title": "Task-Dependent Compressibility of Neural Networks: A Rate-Distortion Perspective",
    "Short Hypothesis": "The compressibility of a neural network is fundamentally task-dependent, and the optimal bit allocation for compression can be determined by quantifying the mutual information between network representations and task-relevant features.",
    "Related Work": "Existing work on model compression (e.g., EMQ, AMP-ViT) focuses on optimizing bit allocation empirically or using heuristics, but lacks a theoretical foundation for task-dependent compressibility. Rate-distortion theory has been applied to generalization bounds (e.g., Sefidgaran et al., 2022) and lossy compression (e.g., Theis et al., 2022), but not explicitly to task-dependent neural network compression. This proposal bridges these gaps by framing compression as a problem of preserving task-relevant information.",
    "Abstract": "Neural network compression is a critical technique for deploying large models in resource-constrained environments. However, existing methods often treat compression as a generic problem, ignoring the task-dependent nature of the information retained by the network. In this work, we propose a novel framework for task-dependent compressibility based on rate-distortion theory. We quantify the mutual information between network representations and task-relevant features, enabling us to derive theoretical bounds on the bit allocation required to preserve task performance. Our approach provides a principled way to allocate bits to layers or weights based on their contribution to task-relevant information. We validate our framework through experiments on vision and language tasks, demonstrating that task-dependent compressibility can achieve superior compression ratios while maintaining task performance compared to existing methods. Our results highlight the importance of considering task-specific information in compression and provide a foundation for future work in this direction.",
    "Experiments": [
      "Experiment 1: Evaluate mutual information between layer representations and task labels for different architectures (e.g., ResNet, ViT, GPT) on classification tasks. Use InfoNCE-based estimators for mutual information.",
      "Experiment 2: Derive rate-distortion bounds for task-dependent compressibility using mutual information estimates. Compare to empirical compression results achieved by pruning and quantization.",
      "Experiment 3: Implement task-dependent bit allocation for compression based on mutual information. Evaluate on vision (ImageNet) and language (GLUE) benchmarks, comparing to SOTA compression methods (e.g., EMQ, AMP-ViT).",
      "Experiment 4: Analyze the robustness of task-dependent compressibility to distribution shifts (e.g., ImageNet-C, CIFAR-10-C).",
      "Metrics: Task accuracy (e.g., top-1 accuracy, F1 score), compression ratio (bits per parameter), and mutual information estimates."
    ],
    "Risk Factors and Limitations": [
      "Mutual information estimation can be computationally expensive for large networks.",
      "Task-dependent compressibility may not generalize well to multi-task or transfer learning settings.",
      "Theoretical bounds may be loose due to simplifying assumptions about the data distribution."
    ]
  }
}
```
